Gathering The Data:¶

I am gathering the data from 3 sources:

  1. Manually downloading an existing file: twitter-archive-enhanced.csv
  2. Programmatically downloading a file from the internet: image-predictions.tsv
  3. Using API to gather and download data: tweet_json.txt

#downloading JSON file

tweets_id = tweets['tweet_id']
error_id = []
with open ('tweet_json.txt', mode='w+') as file:
    for t_id in tweets_id:
        
        try:
            status = api.get_status(t_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            json_str = json.dumps(status._json)
        
        except Exception as e:
            error_id.append(t_id)
            
            continue
            
        file.write(json_str + '\n')

In [6]:
#reading JSON file
t_id = []
fave_count = []
rtweet_count = []
timestamp = []
with open('tweet_json.txt', mode = 'r') as f:
     for line in f.readlines():
            data = json.loads(line)
            t_id.append(data['id'])
            fave_count.append(data['favorite_count'])
            rtweet_count.append(data['retweet_count'])
            timestamp.append(data['created_at'])
            
json_tweets = pd.DataFrame({'tweet_id':t_id, 
                            'favorite_count':fave_count, 
                            'retweet_count':rtweet_count,
                            'timestamp': pd.to_datetime(timestamp)})

Cleaning The Data:¶

I decided to start cleaning some of the messiness in the data first before moving to the quality part. My reason is that i believe that joining the 3 datasets and removing the unwanted columns and rows, will affect columns or rows with quality issues, so i don't need to start working on filling out missing information or correcting wrong ones, or changing datatype if they will be eventually removed.

Tidiness: All 3 tables can be merged

Define¶

Extract the dog rating from the column text, to make sure i'm capturing the dog rating and not other random fractions. I will take the last occurrence only (even if there were more than one rating for more than one dog, it will be more accurate to extract at least one dog rating than extracting a random number.

Code¶
In [54]:
#creating a new list to store the extracted rates
rates = []

#This will cover all occurrences that has the format digit/figit (example 9/10) or digit.digit/digit (example 9.5/10)
rates_extract = lambda x: rates.append(re.findall(r'(((\d+\.\d+)\/(\d+))|((\d+)\/(\d+)))', x, flags=0))

#apply the extract function on the column 'text' in the master dataset
    
twitter_archive_master['text'].apply(rates_extract)

numerator = []
denominator = []

for i in rates:
    
#if the length of the string entry is 0, there is  no rate
    if  len(i) == 0:
        numerator.append('None')
        denominator.append('None')

# only one entry, will add it as my rate 
    elif len(i) == 1:
        numerator.append((i[0][0][0:-3]))
        denominator.append((i[0][0][-2:]))
    
#more than one entry, i will take consider the second as the dog rate (jut in case the first one was not actually a dog rate) 
    else:
        numerator.append((i[-1][0][0:-3]))
        denominator.append((i[-1][0][-2:]))

Tidiness: Breed prediction and confidence prediction are spread on three columns for each prediction

Define¶

Combine the 9 columns in 2 (breed and breed_conf), since the first prediction has the highest confidence, i will go with it unless the prediction was False, then i will go with the next prediction, if that was also False, then i will take the third prediction. If all predictions are False, then i will add "Not Sure" in the breed column

In [63]:
# creating new lists to store the values
breed = []
breed_conf= []

#create a function to store the values in the lists
def pred(row):
    if row['p1_dog'] == True: #this is the highest confidence
        breed.append(row['p1'])
        breed_conf.append(row['p1_conf'])
    elif row['p2_dog'] == True:  #if p1_dog is false, then check p2_dog is True store the values in the lists
        breed.append(row['p2'])
        breed_conf.append(row['p2_conf'])
    elif row['p3_dog'] == True: #if p2_dog is also false, then check p3_dog is True store the values in the lists
        breed.append(row['p3'])
        breed_conf.append(row['p3_conf'])
    else:
        breed.append('Not Sure')    #if all three predictions are False, just add "Not Sure"
        breed_conf.append(0)
In [64]:
# apply the function on my dataset and store the values in new columns
twitter_archive_master.apply(pred, axis=1)
twitter_archive_master['breed'] = breed
twitter_archive_master['breed_conf'] = breed_conf

Results:¶

Rates level is increasing overtime, there are certainly more enthusiasm and participation. We can barely see any rates below 10 after 2016-10

12 is the most frequent dog rate (more than 400), 10 comes next, then 11, then 13. Other rates counts are 150 and less. i think this makes sense, with the unusual and unique rating system that many users are enjoying, people still tend to stay close to 10 in their ratings. in my opinion, this is a human mentality.

Conclusion¶

Limitations:

  • The dogs stages were extracted from the text, so it completely depend on the tweet having one of the stages clearly mentioned.

  • The Rates were also extracted from the tweet text, and while i was able to extract numbers for all tweets, they are not all accurate, the reason is that many tweets had more than rate for multiple dogs

  • Not all tweets had images, so i had to exclude those ones.

  • The dogs breed prediction wasn't correct for all tweets, this resulted in some unidentified breeds.

  • The unique rating system resulted on many outliers in the rates

With the limitation in the data i had, and based on my analysis, these are my "TENTATIVE" findings:

Overall, the data shows an increase in rating scores overtime. We can barely see any rates below 10 after 2016-10. the most frequent rate (score) is 12, then comes 10.

puppo has higher rating average (12.1) among other dog stages. doggo (11.6) and pupper (10.6) come next. However, pupper has the most rating count among all.

The highest correct breed prediction is for the "Golden Retriever" with 158 correct prediction and average rate of 13.6. Which shows that this breed is the most popular breed of dogs here.

Although the increase in favorite_count is more than that of retweet_count, but both counts are strongly correlated.

There are high peaks in both counts in two periods during the year, around end/start of year, and around mid of year. it might be because these two periods are the most active during the year, after holidays and the start of summer
